<section id="overview">
  <h2>Why the Bedroom Matters in Feng Shui</h2>
  <p>In <a href="/fengshui/">feng shui</a>, the bedroom is the most important room in the house. You spend roughly one-third of your life there &mdash; sleeping, resting, and being at your most vulnerable. The quality of Qi (<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>) in your bedroom directly affects sleep quality, health, intimate relationships, and the energy you carry into each day.</p>
  <p>Classical feng shui texts describe the bedroom as a <strong>yin space</strong> &mdash; it should be calm, dark, quiet, and restorative, in contrast to the yang energy of kitchens, offices, and living rooms. When yin and yang are reversed (a bedroom that is overstimulating, cluttered, or too bright), the occupant's health and relationships suffer.</p>
  <p>The principles below come from classical Form School (<span class="chinese-char">形勢派</span>) and Compass School (<span class="chinese-char">理氣派</span>) feng shui, adapted for modern living spaces. They apply regardless of whether your home is a studio flat or a detached house.</p>
</section>

<section id="bed-placement">
  <h2>Bed Placement Fundamentals</h2>
  <p>The bed is the single most important piece of furniture in feng shui. Its placement determines how Qi flows around your body during sleep.</p>
  <p><strong>Headboard against a solid wall:</strong> The wall behind your head represents the "mountain" (<span class="chinese-char">靠山</span>, Kàoshān) &mdash; support and protection. A bed floating in the middle of a room, or with the headboard under a window, lacks this backing. Use a solid, upholstered headboard rather than bars, slats, or open designs.</p>
  <p><strong>Not in line with the door:</strong> Sleeping directly in line with the bedroom door is called the "coffin position" (<span class="chinese-char">棺材位</span>) in traditional feng shui, because the deceased were carried out feet-first through the door. Whether or not you accept this symbolism, having the door directly at your feet creates a draft of Qi that disrupts rest.</p>
  <p><strong>Not under beams:</strong> Exposed ceiling beams above the bed create downward pressure. If beams are unavoidable, orient the bed so the beam runs parallel to the body (along the length of the bed), not across it. A canopy bed or fabric ceiling panel can symbolically deflect the beam's energy.</p>
  <p><strong>Equal space on both sides:</strong> For couples, both partners should have a bedside table and roughly equal space to exit the bed. This symmetry represents balance in the relationship. One partner "trapped" against a wall is a feng shui concern for relationship equality.</p>
</section>

<section id="commanding-position">
  <h2>The Commanding Position</h2>
  <p>The "commanding position" (<span class="chinese-char">指揮位</span>) is one of feng shui's most fundamental concepts. In the bedroom, it means: <strong>you can see the door from bed without being directly in line with it</strong>. Typically, this means the bed is diagonally opposite the door, against a side or back wall.</p>
  <p>The commanding position gives the occupant a subconscious sense of safety &mdash; you can see who enters without being the first thing visible from the doorway. This reduces the startle response during sleep and promotes deeper rest. It is the bedroom equivalent of sitting with your back to the wall in a restaurant &mdash; an instinct shared across cultures.</p>
  <p>If your room layout makes the commanding position impossible (for example, a narrow room where the only wall for the headboard faces the door), place a small mirror so you can see the door's reflection from bed. This provides the same psychological benefit without requiring physical repositioning.</p>
</section>

<section id="colours">
  <h2>Bedroom Colour Guide</h2>
  <p>Colour in feng shui maps to the <a href="/wuxing/">Five Elements</a>. The bedroom benefits from colours that promote rest, warmth, and intimacy:</p>
