  <p>Your personal element (determined by your <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> chart) can refine these recommendations. A person who needs more Water in their chart may benefit from blue accents, while someone with excess Water should avoid them entirely.</p>
</section>

<section id="mirrors">
  <h2>Mirrors in the Bedroom</h2>
  <p>Mirrors are one of the most discussed feng shui topics. The classical position is clear: <strong>avoid mirrors that directly face the bed</strong>. The reasoning has several layers:</p>
  <p><strong>Energy bouncing:</strong> Mirrors reflect and amplify Qi. In a rest space, you want Qi to settle, not bounce. A mirror facing the bed creates a circuit of reflected energy that can disturb sleep.</p>
  <p><strong>The "third person" effect:</strong> In relationship feng shui, a mirror facing the bed symbolically introduces a third party into the partnership. Whether taken literally or as psychology, many practitioners report improved relationship harmony when bedroom mirrors are repositioned.</p>
  <p><strong>Practical compromise:</strong> Mirrors inside wardrobe doors, on a wall perpendicular to the bed (not facing it), or covered at night are all acceptable solutions. A vanity mirror across the room that does not reflect the bed while lying down is also fine.</p>
</section>

<section id="electronics">
  <h2>Electronics and Clutter</h2>
  <p>Classical feng shui cannot address smartphones &mdash; the texts predate them by centuries. But the underlying principle applies perfectly: <strong>the bedroom should contain only what supports rest and intimacy</strong>.</p>
  <p><strong>Screens:</strong> Televisions, laptops, and phones emit light and stimulate mental activity. Their presence converts a yin (rest) space into a yang (active) space. Moving screens out of the bedroom is the single most impactful change most people can make. If a phone must stay (as an alarm), place it face-down, across the room, in silent mode.</p>
  <p><strong>Under-bed storage:</strong> In feng shui, Qi circulates around and under the bed. Boxes, old clothes, and forgotten items stored under the bed create stagnant energy. If you must store items under the bed, keep them organised, in sealed containers, and limited to soft goods (linens, seasonal clothing) rather than emotional objects (old letters, memorabilia).</p>
  <p><strong>Clutter in general:</strong> Every item in the bedroom should earn its place. Books, work documents, exercise equipment, and laundry piles all carry active energy that competes with rest. A clean, minimal bedroom with good air circulation is the foundation of bedroom feng shui.</p>
</section>

<section id="elements">
  <h2>Five Elements in the Bedroom</h2>
  <p>A well-balanced bedroom incorporates all <a href="/wuxing/">five elements</a> in moderation, with an emphasis on Earth (stability) and gentle Fire (warmth):</p>
  <p><strong>Wood:</strong> Living plants (choose low-maintenance varieties that thrive in low light), wooden furniture, green accents. Avoid large or spiky plants; their yang energy is too active for sleep.</p>
  <p><strong>Fire:</strong> Candles (unscented or lightly scented), warm lighting, pink or red accent cushions. Avoid overhead spotlights and harsh lighting &mdash; these create excessive yang Fire.</p>
  <p><strong>Earth:</strong> Ceramics, stone, crystals (rose quartz is a traditional bedroom stone), square or flat shapes, earth-toned textiles. Earth is the most stabilising element for a bedroom.</p>
  <p><strong>Metal:</strong> Small metal picture frames, a clock, circular shapes. Metal should be present but not dominant &mdash; too much creates a cold, clinical atmosphere.</p>
  <p><strong>Water:</strong> A small water feature is calming but controversial in bedrooms. Excess Water can be too yin. If used, keep it small, clean, and placed away from the bed. Images of gentle water (not crashing waves) can substitute.</p>
</section>

<section id="mistakes">
  <h2>Common Bedroom Feng Shui Mistakes</h2>
  <p><strong>1. Bed under a window:</strong> The window behind the headboard means no mountain support. If unavoidable, use heavy curtains and a tall, solid headboard to compensate.</p>
  <p><strong>2. Bedroom as multi-use space:</strong> Working, exercising, and eating in the bedroom blurs its energetic purpose. The bedroom should be reserved for sleep and intimacy. A desk in the bedroom is particularly problematic &mdash; it brings career stress into your rest space.</p>
  <p><strong>3. Too much yang artwork:</strong> Dramatic landscapes, images of solitary figures, water scenes with waves, or bold abstract art create active energy. Choose calm, paired imagery &mdash; particularly for couples (two candles, two flowers, paired objects).</p>
  <p><strong>4. Sleeping in a "dead" corner:</strong> Rooms where the bed is positioned so that Qi stagnates (no air flow, far from the window, behind the door) create lethargy and health issues over time.</p>
  <p><strong>5. Ignoring the ceiling:</strong> Sloped ceilings, heavy light fixtures hanging above the bed, and dark ceiling colours all create downward pressure. If the ceiling slopes, place the bed under the highest point.</p>
</section>
